sailpoint.object

Class IdentityHistoryItem

  • java.lang.Object
    • sailpoint.tools.xml.AbstractXmlObject
      • sailpoint.object.SailPointObject
        • sailpoint.object.IdentityHistoryItem
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, sailpoint.tools.xml.PersistentXmlObject, sailpoint.tools.xml.XMLReferenceTarget

    public class IdentityHistoryItem
extends SailPointObject
    The IdentityHistoryItem class is used to track the history, particularly history involving certifications, for an Identity. At the time of this writing, either certification decisions made against an Identity (for example - role, entitlement, policy violation) or comments made against a particular entitlement for that Identity can be recorded.

      • IdentityHistoryItem

        public IdentityHistoryItem(Identity identity,
                           IdentityHistoryItem.Type type,
                           CertificationItem item,
                           CertifiableDescriptor certifiableDesc)
        Creates a history item for the given item and certifiable. Useful in cases where the certifiable is not the primary entitlement being certified. For example - cases where the certifier has chosen to revoke the required and/or permitted roles for a given role. In that case the certifiableDesc will not match the role on the certification item.

        The constructor is used to pull interesting bits out of the item and certification for later searching/filtering.

        Parameters:
        identity - Identity owning the history
        type - Type of history item to create
        item - CertificationItem in question
        certifiableDesc - identifying the history item

      • IdentityHistoryItem

        public IdentityHistoryItem(IdentityHistoryItem.Type type,
                           PolicyViolation violation,
                           CertificationAction action)
        Creates a history item for the given policy violation. The violation should have been handled outside of a certification, otherwise the CertificationItem constructor should have been used instead.
        Parameters:
        type - Type of history item to create
        violation - Policy violation in question
        action - Certification action performed on the policy violation

        public boolean hasName()

        Return true if the object has a name. This is used by the AbstractSailPointObject and the PersistenceManagers to tell if the name can be used in a search filter.

        It is almost always true, but a few classes like log records do not have meaningful names. Consider using ObjectUtil.hasName(SailPointContext, Class) instead
